  "prompt": "Why does a muscle under my chin cramp painfully when I yawn?",
  "response": "This could be happening due to several reasons:\n\n1. Muscle strain\n- The muscles under your chin (suprahyoid muscles) can become tense or strained\n- Excessive yawning or stretching can cause temporary cramping\n\n2. Nerve irritation\n- A pinched or irritated nerve in the neck or jaw area can cause muscle spasms\n- This might occur from poor posture or neck tension\n\n3. Jaw alignment issues\n- Temporomandibular joint (TMJ) problems can cause muscle tension\n- Misalignment can lead to cramping during jaw movements like yawning\n\n4. Dehydration\n- Low electrolyte levels can cause muscle cramps\n- Not drinking enough water can contribute to muscle tension\n\n5. Nutritional deficiencies\n- Low levels of minerals like magnesium or calcium can cause muscle cramps\n- These nutrients are important for proper muscle function\n\n6. Stress and tension\n- High stress levels can cause muscle tightness\n- Tension can manifest as muscle cramps during movements like yawning\n\nIf the pain is persistent, severe, or accompanied by other symptoms, it's best to consult a healthcare professional to rule out any underlying conditions.",
